40|$|There {{has been}} a {{continuing}} interest among the social scien-tists, both theoretical and applied, in <b>the</b> <b>friendship</b> process (Gump, 1955; Heider, 1958; Lazarsfeld and Merton, 1954; Newcomb, 1961). In a more general sense, friendship {{can be seen as}} one particular type of interpersonal relationship; the helping relationship is another. Can the findings of a study concerning <b>the</b> <b>friendship</b> <b>bond</b> be generalized to other relationships, and to the helping relationship in particular? This paper represents {{part of an effort to}} explore this question. In the literature on <b>the</b> <b>friendship</b> process more attention has been given to <b>the</b> process of <b>friendship</b> formation than to <b>the</b> dissolution of <b>friendship</b> ties (Berscheid, 1969; Byrne, 1969; Campbell, 1958; Newcomb, 1963). From a theoretical point of view it can be argued that the true test of the solidarity of <b>the</b> <b>friendship</b> tie comes at its breaking point. If one could learn more about conditions associated with dissolution, one might learn something about <b>the</b> nature of <b>friendship</b> itself, and perhaps about other relationships. From a practical, or applied, point of view there might be times when the breakup of a tie should be predictable and perhaps preventable. However, by the same token it might be desirable to weaken or terminate a particular tie because of its effects upon the individuals concerned. For the professional practitioner who is involved in and concerned with inter-personal relationships in group helping situations, the con-scious intervention repertoire should include knowledge about the dissolution process as much as about the formation process...|$|R
